Default <- read.csv("https://collinn.github.io/data/default.csv")
Default$default_num <- ifelse(Default$default == "Yes", 1, 0)

Question 1

Part A

ggplot(Default, aes(balance, income)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.25, aes(color = default)) + scale_color_manual(values = c('turquoise', 'red'))

Default status tends to associate more with credit card balance than income.

Part B

model <- glm(default_num ~ balance + income, data = Default, family = "binomial")
odds <- exp(coef(model))

odds
##  (Intercept)      balance       income 
## 9.728329e-06 1.005663e+00 1.000021e+00

When balance variable increases by 1, the probability of default increases by 1.005663 percent. Not all variables include 0 in the data since income cannot be 0. However, if all variables included 0, the intercept of 9.73% would be the probability of defaulting if your balance was 0 and income was 0.

Part C

default <- Default %>%
  mutate(balance.z = scale(balance),
         income.z = scale(income))

scale <- glm(default_num ~ balance.z + income.z, data = default, family = "binomial")

coef_scale<- coef(scale)

odds_scale <- exp(coef_scale)

odds_scale
##  (Intercept)    balance.z     income.z 
##  0.002186252 15.357259851  1.319854899

If balance.z changes by 1, the probability of defaulting increases by 15 percent. When balance and income are average, the probability of defaulting is 0.002 percent.

Part D

Default$fitval <- fitted(scale)

cuts <- c(0.5, 0.2, 0.1, 0.05, 0.01, 0.001)

ggplot(Default, aes(d = default_num, m = fitval)) +
  geom_roc(cutoffs.at = cuts, cutoff.labels = cuts)

As a bank, a high true positive rate is needed (perhaps as high as 90%) to ensure that there is a small chance of false negatives where defaults are counted as non-defaults.

Question 2

set.seed(123)
N <- 200
x1 <- runif(N, -2, 2) # Draw N uniform variables
x2 <- runif(N, -2, 2) # Draw another N variables

# Construct our outcome variable
y <- 2*x1 + 3*x2 + rnorm(N, sd = 2)

df <- data.frame(x1, x2, y)

Part A

ggplot(df, aes(x1, y)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE, color = "red")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

This appears to be a reasonable fit

Part B

ggplot(df, aes(x1, y, color = x2)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE, color = "red")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The negative values of x2 tend to fall below the line of best fit. Positive residuals means they are above the line of best fit while negative means below the line. A plot with x2 on the x-axis and the residuals on the y-axis would be a relatively positive linear plot since the x2 values are negative for lower residuals and positive for higher residuals.

Part C

model <- lm(y ~ x1, data = df)
residuals <- residuals(model)
data <- data.frame(x2 = df$x2, residuals = residuals)

ggplot(data, aes(x = x2, y = residuals)) +
  geom_point()

This plot aligns with my expectations from Part B.

Question 3

Part A

sim <- function() {
    x <- rnorm(100)
    y <- rnorm(100)
  model <- lm(y ~ x)
  ci <- confint(model, parm = 2)
  zero <- ci[1] <= 0 & ci[2] >= 0
  return(zero)
}

res <- replicate(n = 1000, sim())
mean(res)
## [1] 0.947

95% of the simulations contained 0.

Part B

sim2 <- function(N) {
    x <- rnorm(N)
    y <- rnorm(N)
  model <- lm(y ~ x)
  ci <- confint(model, parm = 2)
  zero <- ci[1] <= 0 & ci[2] >= 0
  return(zero)
}

res2 <- replicate(n = 1000, sim2(10))
mean(res2)
## [1] 0.953
res3 <- replicate(n = 1000, sim2(50))
mean(res3)
## [1] 0.952
res4 <- replicate(n = 1000, sim2(100))
mean(res4)
## [1] 0.953

The proportion of simulations containing the true value of 0 should stay around the same as N gets larger.

Part C

runSim <- function(N) {
  x <- rnorm(N)
  y <- rnorm(N)
  
  model <- lm(y ~ x)
  ci <- confint(model, parm = 2)
  return(ci)
}

N <- c(10, 20, 50, 100, 500, 1000)

df3 <- data.frame(x = NA, y = NA)
for(i in seq_along(N)) {
  res5 <- replicate(n = 1000, runSim(N[i]), simplify = TRUE)
  df3[i, ] <- rowMeans(res5)
}

df3$N <- N

df4 <- pivot_longer(df3, cols = c(x,y),
                    names_to = "CI",
                    values_to = "Value")

ggplot(df4, aes(factor(N), Value, color = CI)) +
  geom_point() + 
  labs(x = "Number of Observations", y = "Confidence Interval", color = "Upper/Lower Bound")

The plot shows that the confidence interval decreases as the N increases. However, as the N values get larger, the confidence interval changes less and less. The marginal value of adding more observations increases as our sample size increases.
